GIVEN:\nV = 1.0 V, L = 5.0 m, A = 1.0 mm^2 = 10^{-6} m^2.\nI = 4.25 A, n = 8.5 \times 10^{28} m^{-3}.
\nSTEPS:
(i) Drift Speed (v_d):
   v_d = \frac{I}{nAe}
   v_d = \frac{4.25}{8.5 \times 10^{28} \times 10^{-6} \times 1.6 \times 10^{-19}}
   v_d = \frac{4.25}{8.5 \times 1.6 \times 10^3}
   v_d = \frac{4.25}{13.6 \times 1000} \approx 3.1 \times 10^{-4} m/s.

(ii) Relaxation Time (\tau):
   Relation: v_d = \frac{eE\tau}{m} = \frac{eV\tau}{mL}
   \tau = \frac{m L v_d}{e V}
   \tau = \frac{9.1 \times 10^{-31} \times 5.0 \times 3.1 \times 10^{-4}}{1.6 \times 10^{-19} \times 1.0}
   \tau \approx 8.8 \times 10^{-15} s.
\nFINAL RESULT:\nDrift speed = 3.1 \times 10^{-4} m/s\nRelaxation time = 8.8 \times 10^{-15} s

(i) Difference:
   - EMF (E) is the potential difference between terminals when no current is drawn (open circuit).
   - Terminal Voltage (V) is the potential difference between terminals when current is being drawn. V = E - Ir (for discharge).

(ii) DERIVATION:
   1. Consider two cells in parallel connected to an external circuit. Let V be the potential difference across the parallel combination.
   2. Current from first cell: I_1 = \frac{E_1 - V}{r_1}
   3. Current from second cell: I_2 = \frac{E_2 - V}{r_2}
   4. Total current I = I_1 + I_2
      I = \frac{E_1 - V}{r_1} + \frac{E_2 - V}{r_2}
      I = (\frac{E_1}{r_1} + \frac{E_2}{r_2}) - V(\frac{1}{r_1} + \frac{1}{r_2})
   5. Rearranging for V:
      V(\frac{1}{r_1} + \frac{1}{r_2}) = (\frac{E_1}{r_1} + \frac{E_2}{r_2}) - I
      V = \frac{\frac{E_1}{r_1} + \frac{E_2}{r_2}}{\frac{1}{r_1} + \frac{1}{r_2}} - I \frac{1}{\frac{1}{r_1} + \frac{1}{r_2}}
   6. Comparing with V = E_{eq} - I r_{eq}:
      E_{eq} = \frac{E_1 r_2 + E_2 r_1}{r_1 + r_2}
      r_{eq} = \frac{r_1 r_2}{r_1 + r_2}
